# [PLANTS](../wg/plants.html)

## Summary
The PLANTS (Post-Quantum Low-Latency Archives for Network Security) working group held its first official meeting at IETF 125. The session focused on the administrative transition of the core Merkle Tree Certificate (MTC) specification to a working group item, the adoption of a GitHub contribution policy, and technical discussions regarding monitoring, architecture, and experimental deployment results.

## Key Discussion Points

### Working Group Status and GitHub Policy
*   **Chairs' Introduction**: The chairs (Ross Bush and Tom Ritter) noted that the WG charter is finalized and the main document has been adopted as `draft-ietf-plants-merkle-tree-certs`.
*   **GitHub Policy**: The chairs presented [PLANTS GitHub policy](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-plants-plants-github-policy-00). The WG reached a consensus to use the "Issue Discussion Mode" as defined in RFC 8874.
    *   **Mike Ounsworth** emphasized the need to summarize GitHub discussions back to the mailing list to ensure visibility for those not tracking individual issues.

### Document Update: draft-ietf-plants-merkle-tree-certs
David Benjamin presented [Lettuce Get To Work](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-plants-lettuce-get-to-work-00), covering the latest updates to the core draft:
*   **Terminology Changes**: "Full certificate" renamed to **Standalone certificate**; "Signature list" renamed to **Landmark certificate**.
*   **Architecture Document**: Discussion on splitting the current draft to create a separate architecture document. The architecture doc will provide a non-normative overview of how MTC fits into the broader transparency ecosystem (e.g., interaction with T-Log and static CT APIs).
*   **Log Generations**: To address incident recovery (e.g., CA state corruption or loss of cosigner quorum), the proposal is to treat a CA as a sequence of numbered logs rather than a single log. This allows a CA to "reset" into a new generation if the previous one becomes stuck.
*   **Trust Anchor Formats**: A need was identified for a standard format for MTC Trust Anchors to support non-transparency-enforcing clients and legacy tools.

### Server Monitoring
Brendan McMillian presented [Server Monitoring](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-plants-server-monitoring-00), focusing on how site operators can verify their certificates are correctly logged.
*   **Security Model**: Current CT monitoring often relies on third-party monitors. McMillian argued that for MTC, monitoring should ideally use the same cosigner quorum as the browser to ensure a consistent security model.
*   **Proposed Mechanism**: Adding a new "accumulated log entry type" to the CA log containing verifiable index root hashes. A counter for these entries would allow efficient verifiable searching by monitors.
*   **Discussion**: **Filippo Valsoda** and **David Benjamin** discussed the granularities of these counters and whether the CA or a third party should operate the verifiable index.

### Experimental Results
Luke Valenta presented [MTC experiment early results](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-plants-mtc-experiment-early-results-01) from a collaborative trial between Chrome and Cloudflare.
*   **Performance**: At the median, MTC handshakes were ~9% faster than traditional RSA/ECDSA chains due to reduced bytes on the wire. This gap is expected to widen significantly with Post-Quantum (PQ) signatures.
*   **Reliability**: Most clients were able to update landmarks within hours. Stale landmark rates were around 1%.
*   **Middleboxes**: No major interference was observed, as the server certificate is encrypted in TLS 1.3. When failures occur, the system gracefully downgrades to standard certificates.

### MTC for Private PKI and Pruning
Filippo Valsoda presented [Pruning MTC](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-plants-pruning-mtc-00), demonstrating how MTC can scale down for constrained or private environments.
*   **Isomorphic to X.509**: By reducing the "sub-tree size" to 1 and using a single signature, MTC becomes functionally identical to a standard signature algorithm (e.g., "MTCDSA").
*   **Extensibility**: This allows private PKIs to start with basic MTC and incrementally add features like transparency, cosigning, or HSM optimization (sub-tree signing) as needed.
*   **Discussion**: **Deirdre Connolly**, **Victor Vasiliev**, and **John Gray** expressed interest in exploring MTC for client certificates and private PKIs, particularly to handle large PQ signature sizes.

## Decisions and Action Items
*   **Decision**: The Working Group will use GitHub "Issue Discussion Mode."
*   **Decision**: Accepted terminology changes: "Standalone certificate" and "Landmark certificate."
*   **Action (Authors/Chairs)**: Begin splitting the architecture content from `draft-ietf-plants-merkle-tree-certs` into a new draft.
*   **Action (Chairs)**: Coordinate with the IETF Secretariat to finalize the WG GitHub organization.

## Next Steps
*   **Mailing List Discussion**: Further refine the "Log Generations" recovery strategy and the "Accumulated Log Entry" proposal for monitoring.
*   **Cross-WG Coordination**: Engage with the **TLS** and **LAMPS** working groups regarding Trust Anchor IDs and OID allocations for MTC types.
*   **Private PKI**: Initiate a dedicated thread on the mailing list to discuss the architecture for private PKI use cases.